This year has been a period of significant accomplishment and growth for me as the sole developer for the Regulatory Compliance Management (RCM) system within RSA Archer. I've consistently exceeded expectations, delivering critical enhancements and upgrades while effectively collaborating with my team (Scrum Master, Product Lead, Quality Analyst, and Technical Systems Analyst) within our Scrum framework.

My key contributions this year include:

1.  Migration to CUBE:

Successfully spearheaded the complex migration of regulatory content from Norton Rose Fulbright (NRF) to CUBE, a new vendor. This involved:

Designing, configuring, and implementing three new modules within Archer: Authoritative Sources (CUBE), Change Requests, and Validation.
Developing twelve data feeds to monitor material changes and proactively alert the business.
Creating four data feeds to seamlessly ingest data from the vendor.
Building a dynamic, role-based dashboard that consolidated eight previous dashboards into a single, user-friendly interface.
Implementing a robust notification system, a feature previously lacking in the system.
Writing over 1,000 lines of Python code to interact with CUBE's API and translate data into XML for RCM ingestion, further automating the process. This script was then scheduled using ZEKE for seamless operation.
This migration, initiated in April and first released in September, faced vendor-related delays. However, my persistence and problem-solving skills ensured the timely delivery of a superior, user-friendly product.  This project garnered significant praise from all levels of management during demonstrations. Importantly, no functionality was lost during the migration; in fact, the new system boasts enhanced features, including streamlined change request and validation processes that replace outdated Excel-based methods.

2.  Enterprise Issue Management (EIM) Enhancements:

Efficiently designed and delivered all enhancements to the EIM system under a tight deadline. These enhancements significantly improved the system's functionality and usability, including:
Adding a Secondary Cross-Risk Type for more granular issue categorization.
Incorporating an Issue Identification Date for improved tracking and analysis.
Introducing an "At Risk" flag to highlight critical issues.
Adding an IT Dependency field to capture crucial dependencies.
Replacing "Action Plan Creator" with "Action Plan Owner" to clarify responsibility.
Making themes, assessable units (AUs), and control results mandatory for improved data integrity.
3.  "Compliance Program" Rebranding:

Successfully rebranded all instances of "Compliance Program" to "Assessable Unit" across the RCM system. This meticulous effort involved updating applications, fields, notifications, and data feeds to reflect the new terminology.
4.  Archer Upgrade Support:

Provided vital support for Privacy-related modules (Privacy Incident Reports, Processing Activities, Privacy Risk Assessment, Data Risk Assessment, etc.) during the Enterprise Archer upgrade to v24.8.
Played a key role in supporting the entire RCM instance during the complex upgrade to v24.8, ensuring a smooth transition and minimal disruption to users.
5.  Addressing OSFI Findings:

Successfully addressed OSFI findings related to Issue Management by implementing:

A new internal audit workflow and access control.
New issue types to better categorize and manage issues.
"Plan-for-plan" and "executing issue" statuses for improved tracking.
A "flag repeat issues" feature to identify recurring problems.
A new issue rating methodology for more accurate risk assessment.
Controls to ensure the OECD (Expected Completion Date) is greater than the action plan due date, enhancing timeline management.
Effectively addressed OSFI findings related to Risk Assessment and internal CPE enhancements related to Monitoring & Testing by:

Building functionality within RCM to track regulatory outcomes.
Incorporating "indirect vs. direct monitoring" flags for more precise monitoring.
Developing functionality to track individual control coverage for high-risk AUs, strengthening risk mitigation efforts.
Updating control frequency to be based on residual risk instead of inherent risk, improving the efficiency and accuracy of control activities.
6.  Ongoing RCM Hierarchy Maintenance:

Consistently maintained the RCM hierarchy (regions, segments, line of business, themes, etc.) to reflect organizational changes and ensure accurate data organization. This includes:
Splitting Personal and Commercial Banking into separate entities within the hierarchy.
Aligning RCM Program elements and methodologies, such as the Reliance Oversight Model, by adding new Lines of Business (LOBs) and incorporating BORR as a new standalone segment.
